Title : Paul Marantz
Text : {{Orphan|date=June 2014}}

'''Paul Marantz''' is an [[Americans|American]] [[architectural lighting design]]er, whose work includes the discothèque [[Studio 54]],<ref name="s54">"Studio 54," ''Architectural Record'', Vol. 163, No. 1 (Jan. 1978), pp. 84-87.</ref><ref name="nytp">Finn, Robin. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/29/nyregion/public-lives-from-disco-floors-to-skylines-illuminating-life.html "PUBLIC LIVES; From Disco Floors to Skylines, Illuminating Life,"] ''[[The New York Times]]'', New York, 29 March 2002. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref> the [[Times Square Ball]],<ref name="fmssp">Fisher Marantz Stone, ''Portfolio: Special Projects'', http://www.fmsp.com/port_11.htm. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref><ref name="db">{{cite web|url=http://www.designersandbooks.com/designer/bio/paul-marantz |title=Paul Marantz &#124; Designers & Books |publisher=Designersandbooks.com |date=2014-02-07 |accessdate=2014-06-03}}</ref><ref name="tsball">Kushner, David. [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/12/30/technology/this-new-year-s-eve-technology-will-drop-the-ball.html "This New Year's Eve, Technology Will Drop the Ball,”] ''[[The New York Times]]'', New York, 30 December 1999. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref> the [[Tribute in Light]],<ref name="nytp" /><ref name="fmssp" /> the [[Barnes Foundation]],<ref name="rsbarnes">Smith, Roberta. [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/18/arts/design/the-barnes-foundation-from-suburb-to-city.html?pagewanted=all "A Museum, Reborn, Remains True to Its Old Self, Only Better,”] ''[[The New York Times]]'', New York, 17 May 2012. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref><ref name="fmsm">Fisher Marantz Stone, ''Portfolio: Museums'', http://www.fmsp.com/port_06.htm. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref>
and the [[Burj Khalifa]].<ref name="bk">Lentz, Linda C. [http://archrecord.construction.com/projects/lighting/2010/08/burj_khalifa.asp “Shedding Light on the World’s Tallest Building: Three firms illuminate the Burj Khalifa with alternating restraint and spectacle,”] ''[[Architectural Record]]'', August 2010. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref><ref name="fmst">Fisher Marantz Stone, ''Portfolio: Tower'', http://www.fmsp.com/port_15.htm. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref> He is a founder of the lighting design firm Fisher Marantz Stone.<ref name="nytp" /><ref>Fisher Marantz Stone, ''Our Studio: People'', http://www.fmsp.com/studio_01.htm. Retrieved on 25 April 2014</ref>

== Education and early career ==

Marantz received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Oberlin College]] and did graduate work at [[Case Western Reserve University]] and [[Brooklyn College]].<ref name="bm">Brady, Kevin. "Byzantine Mystique," ''Lighting Design + Application'', Jan. 1999, Vol. 29, No. 1, http://www.ies.org/pdf/archives/1999_01.pdf.</ref> In 1968, he established an [[architectural lighting design]] firm with [[Jules Fisher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archlighting.com/lighting-designers/jules-fisher.aspx |title=Jules Fisher - Architectural Lighting Magazine |publisher=Archlighting.com |date=2011-12-02 |accessdate=2014-06-03}}</ref>

== Awards and honors ==

Marantz has received numerous Lumen Citations from the [[Illuminating Engineering Society of North America]] (IES) for projects including the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]], the restoration of [[Radio City Music Hall]], the [[Times Square Ball]], the [[Houston Museum of Fine Arts|Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]], and the [[Byzantine Fresco Chapel]].<ref name="db" /> He received the International Association of Lighting Designers (IALD) Award for Excellence for the [[Islamic Cultural Center of New York]] and the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]], and he received an IALD Citation for the restoration of the [[Rainbow Room]].<ref name="db" /> ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' architecture critic [[Herbert Muschamp]] described Marantz as a “lighting genius.”<ref>Muschamp, Herbert. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/12/nyregion/nation-challenged-critic-s-notebook-lights-ground-zero-steps-toward-illumination.html "A NATION CHALLENGED: CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK; In Lights at Ground Zero, Steps Toward Illumination,"] ''[[The New York Times]]'', New York, 12 March 2002. Retrieved on 25 April 2014.</ref>

